============================================================
LINUX SERVICE & PROCESS MANAGEMENT CHEAT SHEET
============================================================

-----------------------------
1. WHAT IS A PROCESS?
-----------------------------
A process is a running instance of a program.

View running processes:
ps
ps aux
ps -ef

Real-time process viewer:
top
htop

Search for a process:
ps aux | grep nginx
pgrep ssh
pidof apache2

View process tree:
pstree
pstree -p

------------------------------------------------------------
2. PROCESS STATES
------------------------------------------------------------
R = Running
S = Sleeping (interruptible)
D = Uninterruptible sleep (usually waiting for I/O)
T = Stopped/Traced
Z = Zombie

------------------------------------------------------------
3. SIGNALS
------------------------------------------------------------
Gracefully terminate:
kill PID

Force terminate:
kill -9 PID

Terminate by name:
pkill firefox
killall firefox

Common Signals:
SIGTERM (15) - Graceful shutdown (default)
SIGKILL (9)  - Force kill
SIGSTOP (19) - Pause process
SIGCONT (18) - Resume process

------------------------------------------------------------
4. BACKGROUND & FOREGROUND JOBS
------------------------------------------------------------
Run in background:
command &

View jobs:
jobs

Bring to foreground:
fg
fg %1

Send current process to background:
Ctrl + Z
bg

Detach from terminal:
nohup command &
disown

------------------------------------------------------------
5. PROCESS PRIORITY
------------------------------------------------------------
View priority:
top

Start with priority:
nice -n 10 command

Change priority:
renice 5 PID

Priority range:
-20 = Highest priority
19  = Lowest priority

------------------------------------------------------------
6. SYSTEMD
------------------------------------------------------------
systemd is Linux's init system and service manager.

PID 1:
ps -p 1

------------------------------------------------------------
7. SYSTEMCTL BASICS
------------------------------------------------------------
Start service:
sudo systemctl start SERVICE

Stop service:
sudo systemctl stop SERVICE

Restart service:
sudo systemctl restart SERVICE

Reload configuration:
sudo systemctl reload SERVICE

Check status:
systemctl status SERVICE

Enable at boot:
sudo systemctl enable SERVICE

Disable at boot:
sudo systemctl disable SERVICE

Reload unit files:
sudo systemctl daemon-reload

------------------------------------------------------------
8. LISTING SERVICES
------------------------------------------------------------
List active services:
systemctl list-units --type=service

List all services:
systemctl list-units --type=service --all

List enabled services:
systemctl list-unit-files --type=service

------------------------------------------------------------
9. UNDERSTANDING STATUS
------------------------------------------------------------
LOAD
loaded      = Unit file loaded
not-found   = Unit missing
masked      = Cannot be started

ACTIVE
active      = Running
inactive    = Stopped
failed      = Failed
activating  = Starting

SUB
running     = Process is running
dead        = Stopped
exited      = Finished successfully
waiting     = Waiting for event

------------------------------------------------------------
10. UNIT FILES
------------------------------------------------------------
Common locations:

/usr/lib/systemd/system/
/lib/systemd/system/
/etc/systemd/system/

------------------------------------------------------------
11. UNIT TYPES
------------------------------------------------------------
.service = Service
.socket  = Socket
.timer   = Scheduled task
.mount   = Mount point
.target  = Group of units
.device  = Hardware device
.path    = Watches file/directory changes
.swap    = Swap device

------------------------------------------------------------
12. SERVICE FILE STRUCTURE
------------------------------------------------------------
[Unit]
Description=
After=
Requires=

[Service]
Type=
ExecStart=
ExecStop=
Restart=
User=
Group=

[Install]
WantedBy=

------------------------------------------------------------
13. [UNIT]
------------------------------------------------------------
Description=
Human readable description.

After=
Start after another unit.

Requires=
Must have another unit running.

Example:
After=network.target

------------------------------------------------------------
14. [SERVICE]
------------------------------------------------------------
ExecStart=
Command to execute.

ExecStop=
Command to stop service.

Restart=
Restart policy.

User=
Run as specific user.

Group=
Run as specific group.

------------------------------------------------------------
15. SERVICE TYPES
------------------------------------------------------------
simple
Default. Process starts immediately.

forking
Process forks into background.

oneshot
Runs once then exits.

notify
Notifies systemd when ready.

idle
Starts after all jobs finish.

------------------------------------------------------------
16. [INSTALL]
------------------------------------------------------------
Controls what happens when:
systemctl enable SERVICE

Example:
WantedBy=multi-user.target

Enabling creates a symbolic link inside:
multi-user.target.wants/

------------------------------------------------------------
17. TIMERS
------------------------------------------------------------
Replacement for cron.

Timer file:
mybackup.timer

Service file:
mybackup.service

Start timer:
systemctl start mybackup.timer

Enable timer:
systemctl enable mybackup.timer

List timers:
systemctl list-timers

------------------------------------------------------------
18. TIMER OPTIONS
------------------------------------------------------------
OnBootSec=
Run after boot.

OnStartupSec=
Run after systemd starts.

OnUnitActiveSec=
Run X time after last run.

OnCalendar=
Run on calendar schedule.

Examples:
OnBootSec=5min
OnUnitActiveSec=1hour
OnCalendar=daily

------------------------------------------------------------
19. TIMER FILE STRUCTURE
------------------------------------------------------------
[Unit]
Description=My Timer

[Timer]
OnBootSec=5min
OnUnitActiveSec=1hour

[Install]
WantedBy=timers.target

------------------------------------------------------------
20. .d DIRECTORIES
------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
ssh.service.d/
mytimer.timer.d/

Purpose:
Override or extend configuration without modifying the original unit file.

Example:
ssh.service
+
ssh.service.d/override.conf
=
Final configuration

------------------------------------------------------------
21. .WANTS DIRECTORIES
------------------------------------------------------------
Example:
multi-user.target.wants/
timers.target.wants/

Purpose:
Contains symbolic links to enabled units.

Created automatically by:
systemctl enable SERVICE

------------------------------------------------------------
22. JOURNALCTL
------------------------------------------------------------
View logs:
journalctl

Logs for one service:
journalctl -u ssh

Follow logs:
journalctl -f

Today's logs:
journalctl --since today

Boot logs:
journalctl -b

Previous boot:
journalctl -b -1

------------------------------------------------------------
23. CRON
------------------------------------------------------------
Edit cron:
crontab -e

View cron:
crontab -l

System cron:
/etc/crontab
